<br>
It's what we're made for, after all. Rangers. We might be there to protect the weak, to watch over the Mother's flock or Grandfather Thunder's, but in the end we're as much hunters as any wolf or panther. It's why the animals that don't love us fear us. Because sometimes the hunter inside bleeds through the surface, all fangs and glittering eyes. <br>
<br>
No Moon found me deep in the caverns in Jaggedpine, looking over the corpse of my latest kill. I sliced a thin chunk of meat from the lizard's flank, popped in my mouth raw. Anyone else might have been disgusted by it, but the ghost-wolf actually grinned. <br>
<br>
It was what he would have done, after all. <br>
<br>
&quot;I thought you hated tunnels,&quot; the wolf said. <br>
<br>
&quot;I do.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What are you doing here, then?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Thinning the herd. They're running rampant down here.&quot; I looked away from my prey and grinned at the wolf. &quot;And I'm bloody sick of trying to deal with that zelniak problem. They're going to take over the moon.&quot; <br>
<br>
The wolf settled down on his haunches, grunting like an old man with a paunch. <br>
<br>
&quot;There's something else. I haven't seen you like this since...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Since Everfrost. I know.&quot; I looked away, into the darker tunnels; I could hear basilisks moving there, scaley bellies scrapping along the sandy floor. &quot;Got a fire under me, No Moon. Don't know why. Just a feeling in the back of my mind. Something's coming and I need to be ready.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;So this is practice.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Where's the pixie?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;She's not fond of me when I get like this,&quot; I said, sighing. &quot;I'm no fun.&quot; <br>
<br>
The wolf nodded. <br>
<br>
&quot;Well, I'll leave you to it, then.&quot; He started to walk away, then turned back and grinned again. &quot;You know, you remind me of your father.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;How's that?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The old scoundrel always led with a dagger and swung late with a big old sword, with a dangerous little grin on his face. Like you're doing now. You fight like a rogue, Lest-ye-forget.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I don't fight like a rogue, then. I fight like my da'.&quot; <br>
<br>
The wolf shrugged. Same difference. He trotted off into the shadows and was gone, in the way only ghosts can. <br>
<br>
I grinned again and raced into the darkness, renewed and remembering. <br>
<br>
- Lest-ye-forget Ravenfolly<br>
